## Introduction\par
\par
Every data table or datagrid I've created has been unique. They all behave differently, have specific sorting and filtering requirements, and work with different data sources.\par
\par
It doesn't make sense to combine all of these variations into a single component. If we do that, we'll lose the flexibility that [headless UI](https://tanstack.com/table/v8/docs/introduction#what-is-headless-ui) provides.\par
\par
So instead of a data-table component, I thought it would be more helpful to provide a guide on how to build your own.\par
\par
We'll start with the basic `<Table />` component and build a complex data table from scratch.\par
\par
<Callout className="mt-4">\par
\par
**Tip:** If you find yourself using the same table in multiple places in your app, you can always extract it into a reusable component.\par
\par
</Callout>\par
\par
## Table of Contents\par
\par
This guide will show you how to use [TanStack Table](https://tanstack.com/table) and the `<Table />` component to build your own custom data table. We'll cover the following topics:\par
\par
- [Basic Table](#basic-table)\par
- [Row Actions](#row-actions)\par
- [Pagination](#pagination)\par
- [Sorting](#sorting)\par
- [Filtering](#filtering)\par
- [Visibility](#visibility)\par
- [Row Selection](#row-selection)\par
- [Reusable Components](#reusable-components)\par
\par
## Installation\par
\par
1. Add the `<Table />` component to your project:\par
\par
```bash\par
npx shadcn@latest add table\par
```\par
\par
2. Add `tanstack/react-table` dependency:\par
\par
```bash\par
npm install @tanstack/react-table\par
```\par
\par
## Prerequisites\par
\par
We are going to build a table to show recent payments. Here's what our data looks like:\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers\par
type Payment = \{\par
  id: string\par
  amount: number\par
  status: "pending" | "processing" | "success" | "failed"\par
  email: string\par
\}\par
\par
export const payments: Payment[] = [\par
  \{\par
    id: "728ed52f",\par
    amount: 100,\par
    status: "pending",\par
    email: "m@example.com",\par
  \},\par
  \{\par
    id: "489e1d42",\par
    amount: 125,\par
    status: "processing",\par
    email: "example@gmail.com",\par
  \},\par
  // ...\par
]\par
```\par
\par
## Project Structure\par
\par
Start by creating the following file structure:\par
\par
```txt\par
app\par
\f1\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  payments\par
    \f1\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  columns.tsx\par
    \f1\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  data-table.tsx\par
    \f1\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  page.tsx\par
```\par
\par
I'm using a Next.js example here but this works for any other React framework.\par
\par
- `columns.tsx` (client component) will contain our column definitions.\par
- `data-table.tsx` (client component) will contain our `<DataTable />` component.\par
- `page.tsx` (server component) is where we'll fetch data and render our table.\par
\par
## Basic Table\par
\par
Let's start by building a basic table.\par
\par
<Steps className="mb-0 pt-2">\par
\par
### Column Definitions\par
\par
First, we'll define our columns.\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/columns.tsx" \{3,14-27\}\par
"use client"\par
\par
import \{ ColumnDef \} from "@tanstack/react-table"\par
\par
// This type is used to define the shape of our data.\par
// You can use a Zod schema here if you want.\par
export type Payment = \{\par
  id: string\par
  amount: number\par
  status: "pending" | "processing" | "success" | "failed"\par
  email: string\par
\}\par
\par
export const columns: ColumnDef<Payment>[] = [\par
  \{\par
    accessorKey: "status",\par
    header: "Status",\par
  \},\par
  \{\par
    accessorKey: "email",\par
    header: "Email",\par
  \},\par
  \{\par
    accessorKey: "amount",\par
    header: "Amount",\par
  \},\par
]\par
```\par
\par
<Callout className="mt-4">\par
\par
**Note:** Columns are where you define the core of what your table\par
will look like. They define the data that will be displayed, how it will be\par
formatted, sorted and filtered.\par
\par
</Callout>\par
\par
### `<DataTable />` component\par
\par
Next, we'll create a `<DataTable />` component to render our table.\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/data-table.tsx"\par
"use client"\par
\par
import \{\par
  ColumnDef,\par
  flexRender,\par
  getCoreRowModel,\par
  useReactTable,\par
\} from "@tanstack/react-table"\par
\par
import \{\par
  Table,\par
  TableBody,\par
  TableCell,\par
  TableHead,\par
  TableHeader,\par
  TableRow,\par
\} from "@/components/ui/table"\par
\par
interface DataTableProps<TData, TValue> \{\par
  columns: ColumnDef<TData, TValue>[]\par
  data: TData[]\par
\}\par
\par
export function DataTable<TData, TValue>(\{\par
  columns,\par
  data,\par
\}: DataTableProps<TData, TValue>) \{\par
  const table = useReactTable(\{\par
    data,\par
    columns,\par
    getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel(),\par
  \})\par
\par
  return (\par
    <div className="overflow-hidden rounded-md border">\par
      <Table>\par
        <TableHeader>\par
          \{table.getHeaderGroups().map((headerGroup) => (\par
            <TableRow key=\{headerGroup.id\}>\par
              \{headerGroup.headers.map((header) => \{\par
                return (\par
                  <TableHead key=\{header.id\}>\par
                    \{header.isPlaceholder\par
                      ? null\par
                      : flexRender(\par
                          header.column.columnDef.header,\par
                          header.getContext()\par
                        )\}\par
                  </TableHead>\par
                )\par
              \})\}\par
            </TableRow>\par
          ))\}\par
        </TableHeader>\par
        <TableBody>\par
          \{table.getRowModel().rows?.length ? (\par
            table.getRowModel().rows.map((row) => (\par
              <TableRow\par
                key=\{row.id\}\par
                data-state=\{row.getIsSelected() && "selected"\}\par
              >\par
                \{row.getVisibleCells().map((cell) => (\par
                  <TableCell key=\{cell.id\}>\par
                    \{flexRender(cell.column.columnDef.cell, cell.getContext())\}\par
                  </TableCell>\par
                ))\}\par
              </TableRow>\par
            ))\par
          ) : (\par
            <TableRow>\par
              <TableCell colSpan=\{columns.length\} className="h-24 text-center">\par
                No results.\par
              </TableCell>\par
            </TableRow>\par
          )\}\par
        </TableBody>\par
      </Table>\par
    </div>\par
  )\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
<Callout>\par
\par
**Tip**: If you find yourself using `<DataTable />` in multiple places, this is the component you could make reusable by extracting it to `components/ui/data-table.tsx`.\par
\par
`<DataTable columns=\{columns\} data=\{data\} />`\par
\par
</Callout>\par
\par
### Render the table\par
\par
Finally, we'll render our table in our page component.\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/page.tsx" \{22\}\par
import \{ columns, Payment \} from "./columns"\par
import \{ DataTable \} from "./data-table"\par
\par
async function getData(): Promise<Payment[]> \{\par
  // Fetch data from your API here.\par
  return [\par
    \{\par
      id: "728ed52f",\par
      amount: 100,\par
      status: "pending",\par
      email: "m@example.com",\par
    \},\par
    // ...\par
  ]\par
\}\par
\par
export default async function DemoPage() \{\par
  const data = await getData()\par
\par
  return (\par
    <div className="container mx-auto py-10">\par
      <DataTable columns=\{columns\} data=\{data\} />\par
    </div>\par
  )\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
</Steps>\par
\par
## Cell Formatting\par
\par
Let's format the amount cell to display the dollar amount. We'll also align the cell to the right.\par
\par
<Steps className="mb-0 pt-2">\par
\par
### Update columns definition\par
\par
Update the `header` and `cell` definitions for amount as follows:\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/columns.tsx" \{4-15\}\par
export const columns: ColumnDef<Payment>[] = [\par
  \{\par
    accessorKey: "amount",\par
    header: () => <div className="text-right">Amount</div>,\par
    cell: (\{ row \}) => \{\par
      const amount = parseFloat(row.getValue("amount"))\par
      const formatted = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", \{\par
        style: "currency",\par
        currency: "USD",\par
      \}).format(amount)\par
\par
      return <div className="text-right font-medium">\{formatted\}</div>\par
    \},\par
  \},\par
]\par
```\par
\par
You can use the same approach to format other cells and headers.\par
\par
</Steps>\par
\par
## Row Actions\par
\par
Let's add row actions to our table. We'll use a `<DropdownMenu />` component for this.\par
\par
<Steps className="mb-0 pt-2">\par
\par
### Update columns definition\par
\par
Update our columns definition to add a new `actions` column. The `actions` cell returns a `<DropdownMenu />` component.\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/columns.tsx" \{4,6-14,18-45\}\par
"use client"\par
\par
import \{ ColumnDef \} from "@tanstack/react-table"\par
import \{ MoreHorizontal \} from "lucide-react"\par
\par
import \{ Button \} from "@/components/ui/button"\par
import \{\par
  DropdownMenu,\par
  DropdownMenuContent,\par
  DropdownMenuItem,\par
  DropdownMenuLabel,\par
  DropdownMenuSeparator,\par
  DropdownMenuTrigger,\par
\} from "@/components/ui/dropdown-menu"\par
\par
export const columns: ColumnDef<Payment>[] = [\par
  // ...\par
  \{\par
    id: "actions",\par
    cell: (\{ row \}) => \{\par
      const payment = row.original\par
\par
      return (\par
        <DropdownMenu>\par
          <DropdownMenuTrigger asChild>\par
            <Button variant="ghost" className="h-8 w-8 p-0">\par
              <span className="sr-only">Open menu</span>\par
              <MoreHorizontal className="h-4 w-4" />\par
            </Button>\par
          </DropdownMenuTrigger>\par
          <DropdownMenuContent align="end">\par
            <DropdownMenuLabel>Actions</DropdownMenuLabel>\par
            <DropdownMenuItem\par
              onClick=\{() => navigator.clipboard.writeText(payment.id)\}\par
            >\par
              Copy payment ID\par
            </DropdownMenuItem>\par
            <DropdownMenuSeparator />\par
            <DropdownMenuItem>View customer</DropdownMenuItem>\par
            <DropdownMenuItem>View payment details</DropdownMenuItem>\par
          </DropdownMenuContent>\par
        </DropdownMenu>\par
      )\par
    \},\par
  \},\par
  // ...\par
]\par
```\par
\par
You can access the row data using `row.original` in the `cell` function. Use this to handle actions for your row eg. use the `id` to make a DELETE call to your API.\par
\par
</Steps>\par
\par
## Pagination\par
\par
Next, we'll add pagination to our table.\par
\par
<Steps className="mb-0 pt-2">\par
\par
### Update `<DataTable>`\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/data-table.tsx" \{5,17\}\par
import \{\par
  ColumnDef,\par
  flexRender,\par
  getCoreRowModel,\par
  getPaginationRowModel,\par
  useReactTable,\par
\} from "@tanstack/react-table"\par
\par
export function DataTable<TData, TValue>(\{\par
  columns,\par
  data,\par
\}: DataTableProps<TData, TValue>) \{\par
  const table = useReactTable(\{\par
    data,\par
    columns,\par
    getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel(),\par
    getPaginationRowModel: getPaginationRowModel(),\par
  \})\par
\par
  // ...\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
This will automatically paginate your rows into pages of 10. See the [pagination docs](https://tanstack.com/table/v8/docs/api/features/pagination) for more information on customizing page size and implementing manual pagination.\par
\par
### Add pagination controls\par
\par
We can add pagination controls to our table using the `<Button />` component and the `table.previousPage()`, `table.nextPage()` API methods.\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/data-table.tsx" \{1,15,21-39\}\par
import \{ Button \} from "@/components/ui/button"\par
\par
export function DataTable<TData, TValue>(\{\par
  columns,\par
  data,\par
\}: DataTableProps<TData, TValue>) \{\par
  const table = useReactTable(\{\par
    data,\par
    columns,\par
    getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel(),\par
    getPaginationRowModel: getPaginationRowModel(),\par
  \})\par
\par
  return (\par
    <div>\par
      <div className="overflow-hidden rounded-md border">\par
        <Table>\par
          \{ // .... \}\par
        </Table>\par
      </div>\par
      <div className="flex items-center justify-end space-x-2 py-4">\par
        <Button\par
          variant="outline"\par
          size="sm"\par
          onClick=\{() => table.previousPage()\}\par
          disabled=\{!table.getCanPreviousPage()\}\par
        >\par
          Previous\par
        </Button>\par
        <Button\par
          variant="outline"\par
          size="sm"\par
          onClick=\{() => table.nextPage()\}\par
          disabled=\{!table.getCanNextPage()\}\par
        >\par
          Next\par
        </Button>\par
      </div>\par
    </div>\par
  )\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
See [Reusable Components](#reusable-components) section for a more advanced pagination component.\par
\par
</Steps>\par
\par
## Sorting\par
\par
Let's make the email column sortable.\par
\par
<Steps className="mb-0 pt-2">\par
\par
### Update `<DataTable>`\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/data-table.tsx" \{3,6,10,18,25-28\}\par
"use client"\par
\par
import * as React from "react"\par
import \{\par
  ColumnDef,\par
  SortingState,\par
  flexRender,\par
  getCoreRowModel,\par
  getPaginationRowModel,\par
  getSortedRowModel,\par
  useReactTable,\par
\} from "@tanstack/react-table"\par
\par
export function DataTable<TData, TValue>(\{\par
  columns,\par
  data,\par
\}: DataTableProps<TData, TValue>) \{\par
  const [sorting, setSorting] = React.useState<SortingState>([])\par
\par
  const table = useReactTable(\{\par
    data,\par
    columns,\par
    getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel(),\par
    getPaginationRowModel: getPaginationRowModel(),\par
    onSortingChange: setSorting,\par
    getSortedRowModel: getSortedRowModel(),\par
    state: \{\par
      sorting,\par
    \},\par
  \})\par
\par
  return (\par
    <div>\par
      <div className="overflow-hidden rounded-md border">\par
        <Table>\{ ... \}</Table>\par
      </div>\par
    </div>\par
  )\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
### Make header cell sortable\par
\par
We can now update the `email` header cell to add sorting controls.\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/columns.tsx" \{4,9-19\}\par
"use client"\par
\par
import \{ ColumnDef \} from "@tanstack/react-table"\par
import \{ ArrowUpDown \} from "lucide-react"\par
\par
export const columns: ColumnDef<Payment>[] = [\par
  \{\par
    accessorKey: "email",\par
    header: (\{ column \}) => \{\par
      return (\par
        <Button\par
          variant="ghost"\par
          onClick=\{() => column.toggleSorting(column.getIsSorted() === "asc")\}\par
        >\par
          Email\par
          <ArrowUpDown className="ml-2 h-4 w-4" />\par
        </Button>\par
      )\par
    \},\par
  \},\par
]\par
```\par
\par
This will automatically sort the table (asc and desc) when the user toggles on the header cell.\par
\par
</Steps>\par
\par
## Filtering\par
\par
Let's add a search input to filter emails in our table.\par
\par
<Steps className="mb-0 pt-2">\par
\par
### Update `<DataTable>`\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/data-table.tsx" \{6,10,17,24-26,35-36,39,45-54\}\par
"use client"\par
\par
import * as React from "react"\par
import \{\par
  ColumnDef,\par
  ColumnFiltersState,\par
  SortingState,\par
  flexRender,\par
  getCoreRowModel,\par
  getFilteredRowModel,\par
  getPaginationRowModel,\par
  getSortedRowModel,\par
  useReactTable,\par
\} from "@tanstack/react-table"\par
\par
import \{ Button \} from "@/components/ui/button"\par
import \{ Input \} from "@/components/ui/input"\par
\par
export function DataTable<TData, TValue>(\{\par
  columns,\par
  data,\par
\}: DataTableProps<TData, TValue>) \{\par
  const [sorting, setSorting] = React.useState<SortingState>([])\par
  const [columnFilters, setColumnFilters] = React.useState<ColumnFiltersState>(\par
    []\par
  )\par
\par
  const table = useReactTable(\{\par
    data,\par
    columns,\par
    onSortingChange: setSorting,\par
    getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel(),\par
    getPaginationRowModel: getPaginationRowModel(),\par
    getSortedRowModel: getSortedRowModel(),\par
    onColumnFiltersChange: setColumnFilters,\par
    getFilteredRowModel: getFilteredRowModel(),\par
    state: \{\par
      sorting,\par
      columnFilters,\par
    \},\par
  \})\par
\par
  return (\par
    <div>\par
      <div className="flex items-center py-4">\par
        <Input\par
          placeholder="Filter emails..."\par
          value=\{(table.getColumn("email")?.getFilterValue() as string) ?? ""\}\par
          onChange=\{(event) =>\par
            table.getColumn("email")?.setFilterValue(event.target.value)\par
          \}\par
          className="max-w-sm"\par
        />\par
      </div>\par
      <div className="overflow-hidden rounded-md border">\par
        <Table>\{ ... \}</Table>\par
      </div>\par
    </div>\par
  )\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
Filtering is now enabled for the `email` column. You can add filters to other columns as well. See the [filtering docs](https://tanstack.com/table/v8/docs/guide/filters) for more information on customizing filters.\par
\par
</Steps>\par
\par
## Visibility\par
\par
Adding column visibility is fairly simple using `@tanstack/react-table` visibility API.\par
\par
<Steps className="mb-0 pt-2">\par
\par
### Update `<DataTable>`\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/data-table.tsx" \{8,18-23,33-34,45,49,64-91\}\par
"use client"\par
\par
import * as React from "react"\par
import \{\par
  ColumnDef,\par
  ColumnFiltersState,\par
  SortingState,\par
  VisibilityState,\par
  flexRender,\par
  getCoreRowModel,\par
  getFilteredRowModel,\par
  getPaginationRowModel,\par
  getSortedRowModel,\par
  useReactTable,\par
\} from "@tanstack/react-table"\par
\par
import \{ Button \} from "@/components/ui/button"\par
import \{\par
  DropdownMenu,\par
  DropdownMenuCheckboxItem,\par
  DropdownMenuContent,\par
  DropdownMenuTrigger,\par
\} from "@/components/ui/dropdown-menu"\par
\par
export function DataTable<TData, TValue>(\{\par
  columns,\par
  data,\par
\}: DataTableProps<TData, TValue>) \{\par
  const [sorting, setSorting] = React.useState<SortingState>([])\par
  const [columnFilters, setColumnFilters] = React.useState<ColumnFiltersState>(\par
    []\par
  )\par
  const [columnVisibility, setColumnVisibility] =\par
    React.useState<VisibilityState>(\{\})\par
\par
  const table = useReactTable(\{\par
    data,\par
    columns,\par
    onSortingChange: setSorting,\par
    onColumnFiltersChange: setColumnFilters,\par
    getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel(),\par
    getPaginationRowModel: getPaginationRowModel(),\par
    getSortedRowModel: getSortedRowModel(),\par
    getFilteredRowModel: getFilteredRowModel(),\par
    onColumnVisibilityChange: setColumnVisibility,\par
    state: \{\par
      sorting,\par
      columnFilters,\par
      columnVisibility,\par
    \},\par
  \})\par
\par
  return (\par
    <div>\par
      <div className="flex items-center py-4">\par
        <Input\par
          placeholder="Filter emails..."\par
          value=\{table.getColumn("email")?.getFilterValue() as string\}\par
          onChange=\{(event) =>\par
            table.getColumn("email")?.setFilterValue(event.target.value)\par
          \}\par
          className="max-w-sm"\par
        />\par
        <DropdownMenu>\par
          <DropdownMenuTrigger asChild>\par
            <Button variant="outline" className="ml-auto">\par
              Columns\par
            </Button>\par
          </DropdownMenuTrigger>\par
          <DropdownMenuContent align="end">\par
            \{table\par
              .getAllColumns()\par
              .filter(\par
                (column) => column.getCanHide()\par
              )\par
              .map((column) => \{\par
                return (\par
                  <DropdownMenuCheckboxItem\par
                    key=\{column.id\}\par
                    className="capitalize"\par
                    checked=\{column.getIsVisible()\}\par
                    onCheckedChange=\{(value) =>\par
                      column.toggleVisibility(!!value)\par
                    \}\par
                  >\par
                    \{column.id\}\par
                  </DropdownMenuCheckboxItem>\par
                )\par
              \})\}\par
          </DropdownMenuContent>\par
        </DropdownMenu>\par
      </div>\par
      <div className="overflow-hidden rounded-md border">\par
        <Table>\{ ... \}</Table>\par
      </div>\par
    </div>\par
  )\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
This adds a dropdown menu that you can use to toggle column visibility.\par
\par
</Steps>\par
\par
## Row Selection\par
\par
Next, we're going to add row selection to our table.\par
\par
<Steps className="mb-0 pt-2">\par
\par
### Update column definitions\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/columns.tsx" \{6,9-27\}\par
"use client"\par
\par
import \{ ColumnDef \} from "@tanstack/react-table"\par
\par
import \{ Badge \} from "@/components/ui/badge"\par
import \{ Checkbox \} from "@/components/ui/checkbox"\par
\par
export const columns: ColumnDef<Payment>[] = [\par
  \{\par
    id: "select",\par
    header: (\{ table \}) => (\par
      <Checkbox\par
        checked=\{\par
          table.getIsAllPageRowsSelected() ||\par
          (table.getIsSomePageRowsSelected() && "indeterminate")\par
        \}\par
        onCheckedChange=\{(value) => table.toggleAllPageRowsSelected(!!value)\}\par
        aria-label="Select all"\par
      />\par
    ),\par
    cell: (\{ row \}) => (\par
      <Checkbox\par
        checked=\{row.getIsSelected()\}\par
        onCheckedChange=\{(value) => row.toggleSelected(!!value)\}\par
        aria-label="Select row"\par
      />\par
    ),\par
    enableSorting: false,\par
    enableHiding: false,\par
  \},\par
]\par
```\par
\par
### Update `<DataTable>`\par
\par
```tsx showLineNumbers title="app/payments/data-table.tsx" \{11,23,28\}\par
export function DataTable<TData, TValue>(\{\par
  columns,\par
  data,\par
\}: DataTableProps<TData, TValue>) \{\par
  const [sorting, setSorting] = React.useState<SortingState>([])\par
  const [columnFilters, setColumnFilters] = React.useState<ColumnFiltersState>(\par
    []\par
  )\par
  const [columnVisibility, setColumnVisibility] =\par
    React.useState<VisibilityState>(\{\})\par
  const [rowSelection, setRowSelection] = React.useState(\{\})\par
\par
  const table = useReactTable(\{\par
    data,\par
    columns,\par
    onSortingChange: setSorting,\par
    onColumnFiltersChange: setColumnFilters,\par
    getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel(),\par
    getPaginationRowModel: getPaginationRowModel(),\par
    getSortedRowModel: getSortedRowModel(),\par
    getFilteredRowModel: getFilteredRowModel(),\par
    onColumnVisibilityChange: setColumnVisibility,\par
    onRowSelectionChange: setRowSelection,\par
    state: \{\par
      sorting,\par
      columnFilters,\par
      columnVisibility,\par
      rowSelection,\par
    \},\par
  \})\par
\par
  return (\par
    <div>\par
      <div className="overflow-hidden rounded-md border">\par
        <Table />\par
      </div>\par
    </div>\par
  )\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
This adds a checkbox to each row and a checkbox in the header to select all rows.\par
\par
### Show selected rows\par
\par
You can show the number of selected rows using the `table.getFilteredSelectedRowModel()` API.\par
\par
```tsx\par
<div className="flex-1 text-sm text-muted-foreground">\par
  \{table.getFilteredSelectedRowModel().rows.length\} of\{" "\}\par
  \{table.getFilteredRowModel().rows.length\} row(s) selected.\par
</div>\par
```\par
\par
</Steps>\par
